Using complementary counting:
$P(\max(X_1, X_2, X_3) \geq 9) = 1 - P(\max(X_1, X_2, X_3) \leq 8)$

$P(\max(X_1, X_2, X_3) \leq 8) = P(X_1 \leq 8, X_2 \leq 8, X_3 \leq 8)$

Since the three drugs are independent:
$P(\max(X_1, X_2, X_3) \leq 8) = [P(X_i \leq 8)]^3$

where $X_i \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)$

First, I'll calculate $P(X \leq 8)$ for $X \sim \text{Binomial}(10, 0.7)$:

$P(X \leq 8) = 1 - P(X = 9) - P(X = 10)$

$P(X = 9) = \binom{10}{9}(0.7)^9(0.3)^1 = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821$

$P(X = 10) = \binom{10}{10}(0.7)^{10}(0.3)^0 = 1 \times 0.0282475249 \times 1 = 0.0282475249$

$P(X \leq 8) = 1 - 0.121060821 - 0.0282475249 = 0.8506916541$

Therefore:
$P(\max(X_1, X_2, X_3) \leq 8) = (0.8506916541)^3 = 0.615572379$

Finally:
$P(\max(X_1, X_2, X_3) > 8) = 1 - 0.615572379 = 0.384427621$

Rounding to a reasonable number of significant figures:

