Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: I need to calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton.

The magnitude of spin angular momentum is given by:
$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{s(s+1)}$$

where:
- $\hbar = 1.054571817 \times 10^{-34}$ J·s (reduced Planck constant)
- $s = 1/2$ for a proton (spin quantum number)

Calculating:
$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2}+1\right)}$$

$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{3}{2}}$$

$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{3}{4}}$$

$$L_s = \hbar \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$$

$$L_s = 1.054571817 \times 10^{-34} \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$$

$$L_s = 1.054571817 \times 10^{-34} \times \frac{1.732050808}{2}$$

$$L_s = 1.054571817 \times 10^{-34} \times 0.866025404$$

$$L_s = 9.1347 \times 10^{-35} \text{ J·s}$$

Converting to units of $10^{-35}$ J·s:
$$L_s = 9.1347 \times 10^{-35} = 9.1 \times 10^{-35} \text{ J·s}$$

The answer in units of $10^{-35}$ J·s is approximately 9.1.

